一、圖書作者與內容簡介：<BR>
Recipient of the Newbery Medal for A Single Shard, Linda Sue Park worked as a journalist, a copywriter, a teacher, and now she writes full time.<br />
<br />
Linda Sue Park based this story, A Long Walk to Water, largely on the childhood experiences of Salva Dut, who was born in Sudan. The rebal raided Salva’s village and this attack brought an end to his peaceful and happy childhood. Then, ahead lay the endless walk, suffering, starvation, terror, rage, pain, misfortune, uncertainty.<br />
<br />

<BR>
二、內容摘錄：<BR>
If I die now, I will never see my family again. Somehow, this thought strengthened him enough to keep him from collapsing in terror. (p.11)<br />
<br />
Everything was upside down. (p.17) <br />
<br />
It was hard to keep hope alive when there was so little to feed it. (p.85)<br />
<br />
Would he ever be able to turn his idea into reality? Whenever he found himself losing hope, Salva would take a deep breath and think of his uncle’s words. A step at a time. One problem at a time-just figure out this one problem. Day by day, solving one problem at a time, Salva moved toward his goal. (p.110)<br />
<br />

<BR>
三、我的觀點：<BR>
Boom! An attack started Salva’s long walk to safe place-refugee camp. He lived under great hardship and endured unimaginable treatment in his perilous journey. I am stunned by the plot and almost couldn’t continue reading when I read about the deaths of Salva’s best friend and then his uncle.「 A bad thing, this war. What are you going to do-how will you find them?」Fortunately, after a tough and dangerous walk of hundreds of miles, he arrived at Itang refugee camp, Ethiopia. Due to the collapse of Ethiopia government, the refugee camp had to close. Again, Salva was forced to begin another long walk to another refugee camp-Ifo refugee camp, Kenya. I am relieved and overjoyed that there is a happy ending in the story. Salva was so lucky that he would be chosen to go live in America. He finally could blink away the tears and step into a new life in New York, not having to worry about safety and starvation.<br />
<br />
After receiving education in Rochester, New York, Salva founded an organization and returned to Southern Sudan to dig wells for his people, which makes me admire him even more. This is a long walk to water!<br />
<br />
The fiction, A Long Walk to Water, presented many issues, such as refugee crisis, food shortage, girl education, youth leadership, water resource, hygiene, poverty, and so on. There is so much to think, to discuss. Here, I will mainly discuss the moral issue.<br />
<br />
When reading the fiction, A Long Walk to Water, I am tortured by the thoughts that<br />
<br />
Nya spent half of a morning to reach water while we pay as much the price as a lunch for a cup of babble milk tea.<br />
<br />
Salva struggled against the heat in the desert while we turned down the temperature in an AC room and complain about the cold air.<br />
<br />
Nya and Salva were in fear of losing their family at war while we quarrel with our family members about unimportant trivialities.<br />
<br />
Salva was sometimes in danger of starvation while we usually don’t cherish food.<br />
<br />
Salva’s uncle was brave enough to fight for his people while we Taiwanese just care about the colors of political parties.<br />
<br />
Salva is desperately enthusiastic about learning while we procrastinate as possible as we could.<br />
<br />
I am well aware of how lucky I am to be able to enjoy everything in Taiwan, but I can’t help thinking the following ethical concerns. The following questions and issues flashed into my mind, and I haven’t found any satisfying answers.<br />
<br />
First, we should take care of the weak, the dying and children, shouldn’t we?<br />
<br />
Salva had been abandoned because he was a child, weak, considered a burden on his people, and he often complained about being hungry, causing trouble somehow. Once again, in the desert, Salva’s group came across nine men collapsing on the sand because of the brazing sun. They had no choice but to abandon them owing to the limited water. Salva could do nothing but to mourn for the dying and the deaths.<br />
<br />
Second, is religion all about peace and love? It is religion that has torn the country-Sudan apart, isn’t it?<br />
<br />
Most of the people who lived in the north were Muslim. The government of Sudan forced the people in the south to practice Islam and aimed to become a Muslim country. This led to the south fighting for independence from the north. In human history, there has been so many religious wars and conflicts. So weird! I believe that religion is meant to help us gain peaceful and happy state of mind.<br />
<br />
Third, what is the meaning of war? Why do people wage wars?<br />
<br />
War is a state of armed conflict between groups. It is generally characterized by extreme violence, aggression, destruction, and mortality, often involving military forces. How terrible! It is the war that forced Salva to go on the long tragic walk, and it is the peace land that offers Salva a safe new life. Why do people launch war? Maybe it is because of the darkest side of mankind.<br />
<br />
Fourth, how to solve the refugee crisis?<br />
<br />
As a lost boy, Salva understood the importance of refugee camps. There are still many war-torn countries, which result in its people fleeing out and becoming refugees. Refugee camps with tens of thousands people are common. Large numbers of refugees could cause humanitarian crisis. The retention or abolition of refugee camps and how to solve the refugee crisis are complex problems.<br />
<br />
Last, people are created equal, free and dignified, aren’t they?<br />
<br />
The roads in Rochester are paved while those in southern Sudan are still poorly paved. Salva could hardly believe he was still on the same planet. According to my last paragraph, I doubt that we human beings are created equal?<br />
<br />
Reading Salva’s experiences put me in a very heavy state of sadness and made me critically reflect on human world. He had suffered too much! Much to my astonishment, now Salva has left his comfort zone in New York to his home country to help his fellow citizens by digging wells despite all the opposition from the tribes. His purpose is to bring clean water to those without access to it. Offering fresh, clean water ensures villagers’ health and maintains the life stability in Sudan. Furthermore, children can be discharged of their labor and time on transporting water and put all their energy and time to what matters more-education. Salva has transcended the racial barriers and transformed the lives of a great number of people in Sudan. His project, Water for Sudan, is meaningful and helpful!<br />
<br />
Salva’s story has broadened my horizons and inspired me in a way that bravery and love along with brotherhood could go beyond anything expected of him. He set a good example for me and every responsible global citizen. With determination, perseverance as well as hope, I think I can do something to make the world better!<br />
<br />

<BR>
